then by all means, parents, censor away. Bully for you.

Should it really be the govemment’s job to monitor
such things? The day the government is acting as parent
to my hypothetical children and carefully controlling
what media they’re exposed to is the day I renounce my
citizenship and ﬂee. I

Of course, by then, I probably won’t be allowed to
freely leave the country anyway.

What’s most sickening about Lieberman’s stance on
the whole issue is his shameless hypocrisy. In his state-
ment at the beginning of the war in Iraq, Lieberman
referred to the conﬂict as “a task of high justice, necessi-
ty, and idealism in the best tradition of American princi-
ples and patriotism.”

Apparently, to Lieberman, real war, where real and
often irmocent_ people are slaughtered daily, is American
idealism of the best sort, but killing fake polygonal ene-
mies in an imaginary war is obviously crossing the line.

So, Joe Lieberman, for succumbing to the weak-
minded, buck-passing interpretation of violence in
American youth, then hypocritically turning and cheer-
ing preemptive war, you’ve lost all credibility to me. I
needn’t tell you, sir, not to count on my vote.

