neutralize the situation. To do this, you’re
given a suit of form-ﬁtting cyber armor, that
allows you to ﬁre lasers from your palms,
ﬁre homing bursts from your spinal column
— you get the idea. ,

Despite the fact that Ms. Schneider is a
mercenary worthy of such superior ﬁre-
power, she is completely unable to do two
things at once. She can move, dodge, jump
and shoot; though combining any two of
these activities is ‘strictly taboo. One would
expect more freedom of movement from a
Super Nintendo game. Add some enemies
that can kill with one hit and —-— in a terrible
display of clipping — ﬁre through solid
walls, and the slow, clunky controls become

the knife in this game’s back. Fighting back
would seem like a good idea, save that it’s
driven entirely by a tenible lock-on system.
If an enemy unit is in constant sideways
motion across your ﬁeld of view, you can-
not, under any circurnstanoes, hit them. A
The music ——- a compilation of techno
tracks that seem suﬁicient to make the stal-
wart Vanessa tap her foot in the game —.-
sets the tone for the rage against the
machines. Apart from the violent use of
white space — white walls, white enemy
units, white suit, white everything — the
graphicsare pleasing: Who doesn’t_like see-
ing an athletic woman blowing things up

and contorting herself while she’s at ;it?-

Capcom went to lengths to drive home this
last part, neglecting the fact that, to appreci-
ate the graphics, people have to tolerate the
game ﬁrst.

P.N.03 is fun to watch, but only ‘if
you’re not playing. Granted, that means that
someone else is playing it, and that could
lead to violent strings of expletives, con-

trollers thrown about the room, damage to

the GameCube itself, and/or furniture over-
turned in a frenzied rage. Save your money
and wait for the upcoming Viewtiful Joe;
hopefully, it’ll make up for this painful
experience.

